                  <h3 class="course-title">Unleashing the Leadership Potential in You</h3>

                    <div class="col-lg-6">
                      <span class="subheader">Introduction</span><br>
                      What distinguishes Great companies from just Good companies is that their Leaders are also models for their staff and are committed to developing talent. Developing and sustaining a robust leadership pipeline continues to be the topmost priority and a major challenge in today’s organizations in the face of a VUCA environment.<br><br>
                      “My main job at GE was to develop and nourish talent…The future will not belong to Managers or those who can make the numbers dance.  The world will belong to passionate driven leaders – people who not only have enormous amount of energy but who can also energize those whom they lead” (J Welch) <br><br>
                      Many of existing leaders reached their positions by chance because they happen to be the best engineers, best technical specialists or best accountants parachuted in by circumstances or operational expediency.  This is certainly a recipe for organizational failure.
                      <br><br><br>
                    </div>

                    <div class="col-lg-6">

                      <div class="list-group">
                        <div class="list-group-item list-group-item-warning">
                          <span class="subheader">Key Takeaways</span><br>
                            <ol>
                            <li>To liberate the leader in you to influence Change</li>
                            <li>To discover personal behavior and leadership styles that can make a difference in business performance and personal life decisions</li>
                            <li>To effectively use tested leadership enabling tools and knowledge for continual self-development</li>
                            <li>To gain and acquire practical skills to move on from being a capable Manager to an effective Leader</li>
                            <li>Certification Test</li>
                          </ol>
                        </div>
                      </div> <!-- end list group -->

                      <span class="subheader">Methodology</span><br>
                      This workshop is highly interactive leveraging on pre-course work, mini-lectures, leadership behavioral instruments and group discussions on contemporary leadership challenges.
                      Focus will be placed on learning through self-discovery and self-development. <br><br>
                      This program can be customized to suit the specific needs of the organization

                      <br><br>

                      <span class="subheader">Who will benefit from this Workshop</span><br>
                      <ul>
                        <li>Just about anyone groomed to undertake leadership roles within their organizations</li>
                        <li>Also highly suitable for seasoned Managers and Leaders to take fresh stock of their leadership capabilities</li>
                      </ul>
                    </div> 

                </div> <!-- course 1 -->


                <div id="course2" class="tab-pane fade course-content">
                  <h3 class="course-title">Business Ethics <font color="grey" size="4pt">- Doing the Right Thing</font></h3>

                    <div class="col-lg-6">
                      <span class="subheader">Introduction</span><br>
                      In recent times, there has been much discourse on the need for good corporate governance practices to protect organizations against the unscrupulous actions of business people and even the unconscionable behavior of some misguided employees.<br><br>
                      The usual route to deal with this is to tighten further the rules by introducing even more legislation or policies.  The argument against this route is that no matter how much regulations or risk management systems there are in place, there will always be ways to over-ride these controls, especially if there is no personal resolve to act ethically.<br><br>
                      On the other hand, others have strongly advocated the need to imbue in individuals a moral compass grounded on sound ethical principles that will enable them to make morally correct decisions when faced with difficult choices, especially at the workplace.<br><br>
                      This will be the primary aim of this course

                    </div>

                    <div class="col-lg-6">

                      <div class="list-group">
                        <div class="list-group-item list-group-item-warning">
                          <span class="subheader">Key Takeaways</span><br>
                          <ol class="two-columns">
                            <li>What Ethics is and is not</li>
                            <li>Why Ethics is important in business</li>
                            <li>Why the prevalence of ethical failures despite regulations</li>
                            <li>Moral Principles and Philosophy</li>
                            <li>Code of Conduct explained</li>
                            <li>Corporate Governance and its relevance</li>
                            <li>Personal Data Protection Act</li>
                            <li>Protection from Harassment Act</li>
                            <li>Application issues</li>
                            <li>Certification Test</li>
                          </ol>
                        </div>
                      </div> <!-- end list group -->

                      <span class="subheader">Methodology</span><br>
                      This workshop is highly engaging and interactive involving an interplay of mini-lectures, action learning, case studies and group discussions on contemporary ethical issues.<br><br>
                      This program can be customized to suit the specific needs of the organization

                      <br><br>

                      <span class="subheader">Who will benefit from this Workshop</span><br>
                      <ul>
                        <li>Business leaders especially those directly responsible for promoting good corporate governance practices within their organizations</li>
                        <li>Leaders with responsibility to formulate and train their staff on Company’s Code of Conduct based on strong business ethical principles</li>
                        <li>Functional heads with oversight responsibility over ethics and compliance</li>
                        <li>Any student or practitioner of moral philosophy</li>
                      </ul>
                    </div> 

                </div> <!-- course 2 -->


                <div id="course3" class="tab-pane fade course-content">
                  <h3 class="course-title">Email Etiquette <font color="grey" size="4pt">- Getting the most out of on-line  communications</font></h3>

                    <div class="col-lg-6">
                      <span class="subheader">Introduction</span><br>
                      The advent of electronic mail or email probably ranks highest in the list of greatest technological inventions in this era.  The ubiquitous use of email has a far-reaching impact on how we communicate with others. At the same time, it is also the most often taken for granted.  The resultant effect is a litany of problems in miscommunications, loss in efficiency, personal and organizational conflicts, damaged reputations and creating a festering ground for litigation.
                      <br><br>
                      This workshop aims to help employees improve their online communication skills and to get the most out of the email system.  

                      <br><br><br>
                    </div>

                    <div class="col-lg-6">


                      <div class="list-group">
